name: Extraction of Protein Digestibility Data
description: The project aims to use AI and automation to extract and interpret nutrition data from scientific literature, focusing on amino acid composition. It would then calculate amino acid scores based on various reference patterns and present the results in summary tables or graphs highlighting the limiting amino acid.
capabilities: Computer vision/image recognition, calculation and workflow automation and optimization
data_sources: Scientific research papers
results:
The desired outcomes: 
High accuracy across table types: target table-level accuracy ≥ 95% and field-level F1 ≥ 0.92 for core nutrition fields (nutrient name, quantity, unit, and context).
Comprehensive coverage of complex layouts: ≥90% of tables with identified layout types (multi-column, merged headers, irregular headers) are correctly interpreted.
End-to-end automation: processing of large document sets with minimal manual quality assurance, enabling batch runs with near-zero per-paper intervention.

Powdery mildew is a common fungal disease that affects a wide range of plant species, leading to decreased crop quality and yield. The project seeks to develop a user-friendly web application embeded with AI functionalities that empowers farmers, gardeners, and agricultural enthusiasts to detect powdery mildew and make informed decisions for disease management.
capabilities: Computer vision/image recognition, machine learning algorithm
data_sources: Images and scientific research papers
results:
Desired outcomes:
- Accurate disease detection: Provide users with reliable and accurate identification of powdery mildew in plant leaves. 
- User empowerment: Enable users to make informed decisions about disease management strategies based on detection results. 
- Increased crop health: Contribute to healthier crops, improved agricultural practices, and reduced economic losses due to disease. 
- Usability and accessibility: Develop an intuitive and accessible web interface that caters to users with varying levels of technical expertise.

name: AI for weather prediction
description: The Meteorological Services of Canada (MSC) and Science & Technology Branch of ECCC are actively exploring AI for weather prediction. In 2023, MSC and ECCC's Science and Technology Branch published an AI Roadmap that outlines the path for integrating AI into MSC's forecasting processes through to 2030. This roadmap will drive forward key initiatives, such as the exploration of energy-efficient AI weather models (e.g. GraphCast, ForeCastNet and AIFS) and the development of an all-Canadian model called PARADIS (Physically-inspired Advection, Reaction and Diffusion on the Sphere) a hybrid weather prediction system called "spectral nudging" that combines traditional forecasting methods with AI.
data_sources: ERA5, MSC numerical weather and environmental prediction models
results: This explorating, development and future production will increase ECCC's ability to support earlier detection of weather events and their impacts; improve the timeliness and accuracy of forecasts; improve flood forecasting; and, improve models to more accurately represent how nature really works.

name: Custom course creation tools
description: Environment and Climate Change Canada's Digital Services Branch (ECCC-DSB) built custom course creation tools grounded in training material. Proof of Concept project to explore how generative AI could be used to create training material.
capabilities: Generative AI
data_sources: Generative AI Model knowledge augmented by source documents in a Retrieval Augmented Generation tool.
results: Proof of Concept only, was retired after client  exploration. The system was able to read the content of multiple source documents and create an outiline of a training program based on the source material. It also had tha ability to generate testing tools.

name: Virtual agents for service desk
description: Environment and Climate Change Canada's Digital Services Branch built virtual agents grounded in documented knowledge base for service desk. Proof of Concept project to explore the use of a virtual agent as a primary point fo contact for subject matter experts or for customers. Objective being to reduce the load of triaging service intake requests by providing responses to common questions using corporate knowledge bases, in a natural language.
capabilities: Virtual agent
data_sources: Individual program knowledge bases, intranet content, relevant policies and legislation.
results: The system was able to access multiple sources of information and provide contextually relevant information to answer user questions.

name: Correspondence monitoring tool
description: Environment and Climate Change Canada's Digital Services Branch built a correspondence monitoring tool to monitor and categorize Form Letter emails. Proof of Concept project to explore the automated management of a general delivery mailbox. An AI workflow is scheduled to look at the gd mailbox on a set schedule and read every new email, tag it with relevant information, determine if it is an email of business value, and remove/report emails that are not. Undesirable emails (SPAM,Phishing,form letters,...) are archived and metadata is captured. There is also a reporting capability for the GD mailbox owner to view through a dashboard the landscape of emails received across time.

results: The system is able to determine if an email is of business value or not, augment them with relevant tags, move the ones that are not to archive folders, and generate PowerBI reports. It does not make a judgement on next steps.

name: Automated Detection of Unidentified Fish Sounds in Passive Acoustic Data
description: This completed project used Random Forest and Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) algorithms trained on manually identified fish sounds for detection in passive acoustic recordings. The result is FishSoundFinder, an open-source, user-friendly software tool.
capabilities: Open-source software was developed to automatically detect fish sounds in recordings, allowing fish presence to be estimated without disturbance. An AI-based method was found to outperform traditional approaches and worked well in BC and other regions like Florida.

results: Open-source software was developed to automatically detect fish sounds in recordings, allowing fish presence to be estimated without disturbance. An AI-based method was found to outperform traditional approaches and worked well in BC and other regions like Florida.

name: News topic detection tool
description:
Problem: Identifying emerging topics that are relevant to DFO's mandate. Manually tracking and assessing the relevance of news content is time-consuming and prone to oversight, especially when trying to align it with existing internal knowledge.

Objective for AI: Use large language models and topic clustering to automatically analyze emerging news topics and determine their relevance to DFO. This approach will also surface what knowledge or resources DFO already possesses to address those topics, enabling faster, more informed responses and strategic planning.
capabilities: The system uses large language models and topic clustering to automatically analyze emerging news topics and assess their relevance to DFO. It identifies connections between external developments and internal priorities.
data_sources: Canadian Science Advisory Secretariat published documents
results: Expected to have digitized results in an interactive dashboard to query and look at

name: Oceanographic Anomaly Detection
description: The goal of this project is to apply machine learning to detect anomalies in conductivity, temperature, depth (CTD) data, highlighting significant physical phenomena in the state of the ocean for closer investigation by scientists.

name: IM Chatbot
description: Chatbot to answer Information Management related questions, based on information available on the IM intranet site.

name: GitHub Copilot
description: GitHub Copilot is being piloted at DFO aimed at enhancing developer productivity and exploring the operational value of AI-assisted coding.

name: Remote Observation of Watercraft on Roads
description:
The Aquatic Invasive Species Program is proposing to launch a pilot initiative aimed at addressing a critical knowledge gap in our understanding the spread of aquatic invasive species.  Invasive species can attach to boats, trailers, and related equipment—a process commonly referred to as the "stowaway pathway"—which enables their unintentional spread across ecosystems when watercraft are transported between water bodies. The AIS Program is seeking to understand watercraft movement into Canada via international land border crossings. Currently, the extent of this "stowaway" pathway remains largely unquantified.
To address this, the pilot will deploy remote camera systems at select border entry points to capture imagery of incoming vehicles. Leveraging machine learning, the system will automatically identify and flag images containing watercraft.

name: PSSIFence
description:
Problem: DFO inspects hours of underwater camera footage to count and identify fish species through fence counts, which is a structure installed across a river or stream to monitor fish population. The amount of hours needed to review underwater footages will need to increase in order fulfil oblgiations as it is not sustainable.
Objective for AI: Replace manual analysis of fence videos to determine salmon counts by species.  Leveraging advanced computer vision technology, reducing the manual effort required, and providing more accurate and timely data.
capabilities: The AI system detects and counts salmon species from camera footages
data_sources: Data source: Science Branch - Stock Assessment Lab. Data type : video
results: Users will be informed in text with numbers and types of salmons that appear in the footage.

name: PSSIScaleAging
description:
Problem: DFO-Sclerochronlogy Lab is responsible for fish age analysis services to clients across British Columbia and the Yukon and is responsible for approximately 80,000 salmon scale aging assessments a year. Technicians require extensive experience and knowledge to provide scale aging assessment. With increasing assessments and limited resources, it will only result in limited analysis performed. 
Objective for AI: Automate and improve the process for lab technicians to analyze scale imprints from salmon to determine its age. By leveraging computer vision, particularly through deep learning models like Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), the process becomes more efficient and accurate to assess salmon age.
capabilities: The AI system monitors growth and predicts salmon age from scale images
data_sources: Data source: Science Branch - Fish Ageing Lab. Data type: Image
results: User will be informed in text with number of ring grown each season and the age of salmon

name: Pacific RAG Chatbot
description:
Problem: Information detailing DFO policy and governance, science and research, and main activities in BC and the Yukon for management of fisheries are offered on the DFO Pacific Fisheries internet site. However, it may be difficult to obtain specific key information when searching the website for relevant information. 
Objective for AI:  Aligning on DFO's data strategy and provide information and data that is findable, accessible, interoperable and reuseable is priority, a custom AI chatbot  uses retrievable augmented generation (RAG) to retrieve information from the DFO Pacific Fisheries internet site.
capabilities: The AI system returns key information including document and image from DFO Pacific website based on the meaning of user prompt.
data_sources: Data source: DFO public website. Data type: image and text
results: Users will be informed with text and image for what information they are searching

name: PSSIOCR
description:
Problem: Many DFO programs store thousands of documents (scanned, paper-based, unstructured records) that contain valuable information for reporting, tracking, and decision making. Due to the volumn of documents, it is often unfeasable to transfer this information into a digital structured format. This has created significant limitations for the availability, timeliness and quality of data needed to make Pacific salmon management decisions. 
Objective for AI: To help modernize data workflows and ensure long-term preservation and usability of valuable historical data by automating the extraction of document content into a structured format through the use of OCR software.
capabilities: Sort scanned PDFs by document type, extract document information into a structured format, and support manual review/verification of data.
data_sources: Fish slips, compliance and inspection reports, BC16 documents, puchase slips, dockside reports, logbooks, and sea obersver reports sourced from various programs were used in training custom OCR models. This includes unclassified, protected A, and protected B data.
results: The AI system was integrated as part of a script alongside OCR and blob storage to extract content from documents, allow correction/verification of data on a web application, and storage in Microsoft Fabric tables. Subject matter experts were given access to Microsoft Fabric, to search, transform, and migrate the data into their own databases.

name: Factoid Finder Tool
description:
Problem: Efficiently extracting and navigating information from machine-readable PDFs. Traditional keyword-based search methods often fall short in identifying contextually relevant content, making it difficult for users to locate specific information within large document libraries.
Objective for AI: The Factoid Finder addresses this issue by extracting text from PDFs to build searchable content libraries. It leverages Small Language Models to implement semantic search techniques, enabling users to retrieve contextually relevant passages from within the documents more effectively.
capabilities: Reduce the manual labour required for reviewing and organizing knowledge from documents
data_sources: PDF libraries of scientific and grey literature
results: Reduce the manual labour required for reviewing and organizing knowledge from documents

name: Optical Character Recognition Data transcription tool
description:
Problem: Science observations and research requires transcription and validation from hand-written field notes, including historical information.
Objective for AI: Digitize non-machine-readable (handwritten) documents and extracts characters into a digital format, to deliver productivity gains and improve availability of data from paper forms. Piloted with  ~100 year old salmon observations and present-day salmon stream inspection logs.
capabilities: Extracts characters into structured digital formats, including tabular data.
data_sources: BC16 Historical Data
results: Expected to have digitized results in an interactive dashboard to query and look at

name: Data Validation Tool
description:
Problem: Digitizing handwritten or non-machine-readable documents using optical character recognition (OCR) often introduces transcription errors, which can compromise data quality and usability. These inaccuracies make it difficult to rely on the extracted information for analysis or integration into standardized systems.
Objective for AI: Leverage large language models to detect and correct OCR-induced errors by applying intelligent validation rules. The goal is to propose accurate corrections and normalize the extracted data into a consistent, standardized format, ensuring higher reliability and interoperability across systems.
capabilities: Automated data validation will reduce the time that transcribers spend detecting and correcting data entry errors, and help to standardize responses prior to entry into a database.
data_sources: Area Stream Inspection Logs from Pacific Regions
results: Expected to have digitized results in an interactive dashboard to query and look at

name: AI-Assisted CTD Quality Control Tool
description:
Problem: Quality control of Conductivity, Temperature, Depth (CTD) data is a labor-intensive process that places a significant manual burden on oceanographers. This repetitive task diverts their time and expertise away from more valuable scientific analysis and decision-making activities.
Objective for AI: Implement an AI-powered tool that automatically flags CTD profile scans for deletion or preservation during the quality control process. This will support oceanographers in performing quality control more efficiently and accurately, enhancing productivity and allowing them to focus on tasks that require their specialized knowledge.
capabilities: Binary classification of tabular oceanographic data is performed using a combination of Gaussian Mixture Models to first create clusters of similar data and Multi-Layer Perceptrons to perform classification of the individual rows of sensor scans within each cluster.
data_sources: The model is trained on historical Conductivity, Temperature, Depth (CTD) data collected and processed by DFO Pacific Region. The model will be applied to support quality control of new CTD collected by the region.
results: The tool will facilitate time-consuming quality control tasks, improving productivity. The recommendation flags will support more rapid identification of bad data to be deleted and will support support faster and more reliable verification of the middles of CTD profiles where time-constraints prevent highly-detailed attention.

name: Characterizing Environmental Extremes Using Machine Learning
description: This project developed a machine learning-based method to identify environmental extremes by segmenting data into regions with consistent conditions (e.g., temperature, oxygen, acidity). Extremes were defined based on historical variability within each region, enabling more targeted and context-aware analysis of environmental changes.

name: Improving Streamflow Simulations with Neural Network Post-Processing
description: This project applied neural networks to post-process streamflow outputs from the WRF-Hydro model, improving alignment with observational data. The approach serves as a downstream calibration step, building synergy between traditional hydrologic calibration methods and modern AI techniques.

name: Labels Pilot
description: We are looking into using Labels back end for smart labels as well as a free copilot agent for the department to use in order to validate a user's classification.

name: Analyse development programming alignment
description: To understand what portion of Canada’s development programming in agriculture and food aligns with the Ceres2030 10 high-impact interventions to meet the United Nation Sustainable Development Goal 2 towards “zero hunger.” The aim of this work is to use machine learning to extract certain project characteristics, features and details at the output and activity level to enhance the details currently found in existing departmental reporting. This will help to elaborate causal relationships of outputs and activities that are buried within project documents and project outcomes presented in reports. This process will lead to building a platform for portfolio analysis and future predictive analysis.  This approach will inform the extent to which interventions and approaches, either individually and jointly, are in alignment with the Ceres2030 Interventions and meeting strategic, programmatic and policy needs and beyond.
capabilities: The system uses custom-trained NLP pipelines to extract structured data—intervention types and outcomes—from unstructured reports. These are algorithmically mapped to high-impact strategies from the Ceres2030 framework. The data is integrated into dashboards for visualization and decision support. Technologies include semantic matching, classification models, and predictive modeling to assess intervention effectiveness across agri-food systems.
data_sources: Annual and end-of-project reports; Management summaries; CFO Stats
results: The evolution of newer technologies and competing priorities led to the project being discontinued

name: Disinformation dashboard
description: Using Watson Natural Language Understanding for named entity recognition to identify key organization, individuals and locations.  IBM Watson® Natural Language Understanding uses deep learning to extract meaning and metadata from unstructured text data.
capabilities: The system uses IBM Watson Natural Language Understanding for Named Entity Recognition to automatically extract and categorize people, organizations, and locations from media sources. It scores articles for relevance to foreign policy and reputational risk, and applies analytical methods to detect disinformation narratives and patterns of foreign interference, providing clear support for analysts.
data_sources:
Traditional media (e.g., news articles)
Social media (e.g., Twitter, RSS feeds)
Factiva and other licensed content aggregators
results: The project was discontinued due to persistent AI accuracy and consistency issues, integration difficulties with existing business workflows, and a lack of operational sustainability. Superior internal solutions like DocCracker outperformed the system in performance and usability. Additionally, unresolved privacy and compliance risks related to social media data usage further limited the project's viability.

name: Financial risk monitoring
description: Leverage AI and ML techniques to to provide regular, proactive risk monitoring on Global Affairs Canada's financial data with an objective to reduce the level of financial risk in mission transactions.  Vendor's off-the-shelf internal audit tool customized with Global Affairs Canada specific AIalgorithm development for financial monitoring.

results: This was an exploratory experimentation and ultimately the tool was not put into production due to IT/technical and business constraints, and the low overall fit and value proposition.

name: Data entry for grants and contributions
description: AI-assisted data entry for Grants and Contributions to improve data accuracy and consistency across several critical data fields. This is expected to lead to better investment planning, prioritizing, accountability, monitoring and reporting of Canada's contribution to international assistance.  Analysis of project documentation and data. Data preparation and identification of most pertinent project documentation. Implementation of various AI natural language processing models to analyse project documentation and data coding. Optimization and fine tuning the model to assess and attain accuracy. AI models to generate project coding and robotic process automation (upcoming) to assist in the automation of data entry. Tools and processes for monitoring and maintenance of the tools.
capabilities: The solution uses Azure AI Document Intelligence and AI Vision to extract structured text from grant documents, then applies LLMs in Azure ML Studio to convert content into JSON for system ingestion. An NLP and LLM ensemble classifies projects by DAC codes, policy markers, and countries, supporting bilingual processing and batch automation.

results: Partly in production.  Integration with new Gs&Cs application in progress. This is expected to lead to better investment planning, prioritizing, accountability, monitoring and reporting of Canada's contribution to international assistance.

name: Export Control On-Line System (EXCOL)
description: EIPA permits are automatically granted by the NEICS & NEXCOL systems if specific conditions are met, through rules-based techniques (e.g., available quotas for importers/exporters). EXCOL is an interactive and computerized application that allows clients to submit export applications and certificates on-line using Secure Channel.

results:
NEXCOL is designed to facilitate the interdepartmental
assessment of strategic good permit eligibility, and it provides a level of access to Canadian exporters to facilitate the permitting and reporting process.

name: Enhanced Reporting Capabilities for International Assistance Grants and Contributions
description: Global Affairs Canada is responsible for managing most of Canada's international assistance funding, and its staff are often required to assess alignment between project funding and policy objectives. Assessing projects against evolving and emerging policy markers is time consuming, and GAC looked for risk-informed methods to automate these assessments. Using manual assessments as a gold standard, GAC tested approaches to understand the trade-off between accuracy, transparency, and cost. It implementd methods using generative AI to encode the assessment frameworks and the domain knowledge of experienced evaluators. This approach assigns policy markers based on project summaries generated during GAC’s existing processes. Multiple policy markers have been implemented within a web-based tool which is currently in validation. The tool has an accuracy comparable to expert assessors and produces an accompanying explanation to allow expert oversight.
capabilities: Selects most relevant policy markers for project descriptions enterred into the app
data_sources: User input
results: The tool's accuracy is comparable to that of expert assessors.

name: Document Analyzer
description: Document Analyzer streamlines the evaluation process by automating the structured analysis of multiple documents, enabling faster review and synthesis of findings. It supports standardized assessments, reduces manual effort, and helps evaluators identify trends, risks, and lessons learned more efficiently. The tool also facilitates the adoption of generative AI within evaluation teams, improving both the speed and quality of evaluation outputs for program and project assessments.
data_sources: EDRMS, InfoBank, and SharePoint. The types of documents include technical reports, research papers, financial reports, project management documentation, partner and annual project reports, evaluation reports, audits, and transcripts from interviews or meetings.
results: DocumentAnalyzer streamlines the evaluation process by automating the structured analysis of multiple documents, enabling faster review and synthesis of findings. It supports standardized assessments, reduces manual effort, and helps evaluators identify trends, risks, and lessons learned more efficiently. The tool also facilitates the adoption of generative AI within evaluation teams, improving both the speed and quality of evaluation outputs for program and project assessments.

name: GAC Translate
description: Provides the ability for users to upload and get translations of documents up to protected B data, from most world languages. The use case was driven by the need to quickly translate documents with unknown content that might contain personal information, to be able to determine if they require immediate and official translation. Originally built for translation of Protected B Information for the Canadian Ombudsperson for Responsible Enterprise. Since expanded to all GAC users.
data_sources: Any user uploaded documents
results: The AI tool enhances translation of Protected B information by allowing users to upload documents instantly and receive immediate translations. This enables rapid assessment of content urgency or priority, streamlining workflows and supporting response in sensitive cases handled by the Canadian Ombudsperson for Responsible Enterprise

name: Situational Awareness
description: Situational Awareness is a custom application built by the National Research Council, which allows Global Affairs Canada to proactively monitor information originating from traditional news and social media sources.  The platform uses Support Vector Machine libraries to score the news articles as they are ingested.
capabilities: The platform utilizes scheduled data ingestion via Factiva and Twitter APIs, retrieving news and tweets at 15-minute intervals. Textual analysis employs machine translation, geo-tagging, named entity recognition, quotation attribution, and VAD sentiment scoring. Relevance is computed using a support vector machine, while VAD quantifies valence, arousal, and dominance for quoted statements. Results are visualized as ranked lists, interactive maps, and stance matrices for advanced insight.
data_sources: Factiva and RSS feeds
results: GAC's partnership with NRC to develop the situational awareness platform enabled early deployment of a scalable NLP-based solution for GAC clients. This initiative advanced GAC’s technical capabilities, expediting subsequent tool development like DocCracker. Given GAC's development of improved, cost-effective implementations elsewhere, further investment in the original platform would have yielded limited ROI. Tool retired.

name: Document Cracker
description: To manage the wealth of information, a document search and analysis tool called Document Cracker was developed to help officials quickly find the information they need. Document Cracker enables users to search across a large volume of documents using a sophisticated indexing platform and automatically monitor new documents for specific topics, emerging trends, and mentions of key people, locations, and organizations. These features allow officials to quickly identify pressing issues, formulate a preferred stance, and track the evolving stances of other countries.
capabilities: The document cracker solution uses Azure Cognitive Search and Databricks for ingestion, enrichment, and entity recognition; Power Automate and Logic Apps for workflow automation; and GPT-3 for embedded document summarization. It applies machine learning for sentiment analysis and named entity recognition, and integrates with Power BI for visualization. Custom NLP skillsets extract GAC-specific entities, and a lightweight LLM proxy supports flexible model interfacing. The system runs in a secure cloud environment.
data_sources: Unclassified internal GAC documents—such as SITREPs, readouts, and statements—and external news via Factiva.
results: The Doc Cracker solution was developed to address overwhelming volumes of daily reports and external data during. Manual processing was unsustainable, and analysts needed a faster way to extract insights. The solution centralized reporting, reduced time spent searching, and improved situational awareness. It helped policy teams respond more effectively in multilateral forums and supported faster, more coherent policy development.

name: AI-generated briefing notes
description: AI-generated briefing notes using internal and external data. (experimentation phase) Experimenting with OpenAI cognitive services for AI-generated briefing notes. This is an attempt to generate a first cut/draft templated briefing for policy analysts on which to review, validate and augment to create a final document. This area is also of interest to Strategic Planning, Policy and Operations who has supported Global Affairs Canada's Data Science team's experimentation.

This streamlines workflows, enables staff to focus on refining content, and demonstrates the practical value of generative AI, paving the way for future enhancements and broader integration within the department.

It will assist the CFO's Statistical and Reporting Unit (SWS) to improve it's Back-end QA process, cathing errors more quickly and reliably, leading to better data. results: Advances citizen-led development to empower staff in creating tailored digital solutions that meet operational needs. This approach fosters collaboration, builds data literacy, and supports strategic alignment across departments. By expanding AI capabilities and embedding responsible AI practices, GAC aims to enhance decision-making, streamline workflows, and improve service delivery. The accruing benefits include stronger data governance, increased confidence in organizational data, and a culture of innovation.

These chatbots will interact with departmental data, files, URLs, SharePoint, and the intranet, thereby improving accessibility and efficiency within the organization. The enterprise AI self-serve platform allows GAC staff to leverage a variety of AI models, tools and capabilities across GAC's enterprise data systems. This platform will also allow staff to prototype workflows and experiment with new technology as it is added to the platform.

1) Entra ID integration

4) SharePoint Integration and user  knowledge base creation

name: Trade Commissioner Service website chatbot (Digital Experience Platform - DXP)
description: As a strategic initiative to foster and promote trade, the Trade Commissioner Service (TCS) is deploying a refreshed website to optimize end-user experience for Canadian exporters. In addition to deploying the new website through the Digital Experience Platform project, a public-facing chatbot is targeted for release in the fall 2025 to further enhance the experience. Generative response generation using Microsoft Copilot Studio referencing the TCS website with citation support; semantic matching and trigger phrase refinement for FAQ discovery; keyword-based redirection to Other Government Departments ; and telemetry logging via Azure Application Insights to capture user messages, triggered topics, session activity, and engagement metrics. These capabilities are supported by a multi-environment deployment pipeline (Dev, QA, Staging, Prod), automated unit testing via Pytest, and performance testing using Locust, JMeter, and Azure Load Testing.
capabilities: Generative response generation, semantic matching and trigger phrase refinement; keyword-based redirection; and telemetry logging
data_sources: Trade Commissioner Service (TCS) website as primary knowledge base; TCS event website; curated set of 50 bilingual frequently asked questions.
results: DXP is expected to improve service efficiency and client engagement by automating routine interactions, simplifying content publishing, and tailoring communication. Staff can prioritize exporters with greater potential while maintaining service coverage for others. The platform improves tracking of client activity and service outcomes for operational planning and resource allocation. This will increase the reach and effectiveness of the Trade Commissioner Service without increases in staffing.

Science-GPT

results: Tool(s) deployed to assist scientists with review of chemicals

name: Integrity trends analysis tool
description: An AI-powered solution designed to streamline verification activities by automating the identification and assessment of fraud risks in temporary resident applications. By integrating various data sources and analyzing trends, the tool provides comprehensive risk profiles and detects patterns indicative of fraud. Its intuitive user interface and detailed reporting capabilities enhance the efficiency, accuracy, and productivity of verification activities, enabling proactive measures against potential fraud trends. ITAT uses data elements found and recorded in IRCC’s Global Case  Management System (GCMS) and the Integrated Payment Revenue  Management System (IPRMS). The data consists primarily of information provided directly by clients through their TR applications and supporting  documents. ITAT also uses information that CBSA and other partners have  recorded in the GCMS. IRCC does not use external data sources such as social media.

name: Impact Assessment Decision-Support Agent (IADSA)
description: The Impact Assessment Decision-Support Agent (IADSA) will leverage agentic artificial intelligence (AI) to reduce the time and effort required to complete Impact Assessment reviews while ensuring transparency, accountability, and compliance with Government of Canada requirements. Current review processes are resource-intensive, requiring analysts to examine large volumes of technical studies, geospatial data, and public submissions. IADSA will assist by summarizing information, modeling potential impacts, and providing structured recommendations for human review and approval. This will improve the efficiency and consistency of decision dashboards, strengthen compliance monitoring, and enhance engagement with groups, stakeholders, and the public - while ensuring final decisions remain human-led and accountable.
capabilities: Summarizes complex information, conducts agentic search, models impacts, and analyzes geospatial data. Supports public engagement, decision dashboards, and compliance monitoring by providing structured insights for human review and approval.
data_sources: The unclassified, publicly available IAAC Registry. https://www.iaac-aeic.gc.ca/050/evaluations?culture=en-CA
results: When implemented, IADSA is expected to reduce manual analysis time by more than 20%, accelerate preparation of engagement and compliance materials, and improve decision dashboards with timely, accurate summaries. It will enhance transparency, efficiency, and evidence-based decision-making across Impact Assessment reviews.

Results are communicated to clients in the form of pre-assessment letters issued by the Canadian Intellectual Property Office with information on how to address these deficiencies/issues. name: Radia Generative Artificial Intelligence Platform (Proof-of-Concept)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description:
Radia Proof-of-Concept is an experimentation platform developed by the Communications Research Centre to provide employees with advanced generative artificial intelligence tools and explore efficiency improvements. 
Launched in 2024, it enables interaction with LLMs and autonomous agents through application programming interfaces. Hosted in a departmental cloud environment, it can integrate with internal knowledge bases and systems. It supports summarisation, drafting, translation, code assistance, data analysis, and text or visual content generation. Users can also design automated workflows. The goal is to reduce repetitive tasks, improve productivity, and explore safe, responsible AI adoption in departmental operations. The application is restricted to unclassified information. 
Radia Proof-of-Concept uses a combination of open-source and proprietary components. The platform is extended with custom integrations and enhancements for intelligent agents, knowledge base connectivity, and departmental system integration. Provides access to various proprietary models and services through application programming interfaces.
capabilities: Provides document summarization, question answering, document drafting, translation, data extraction including tables, coding assistance, file uploads, knowledgebase integration, custom presets, and multi-model side-by-side response comparisons.
data_sources: Inputs during use are limited to user-provided public or unclassified content such as documents, text, images and data. May include web data. No classified or sensitive information is used.
results: Intended to streamline routine tasks for federal public servants, enabling faster document analysis, drafting, translation, coding, and data extraction. Implementation reduces manual workload, speeds up turnaround, and improves accuracy and productivity. Radia Proof-of-Concept has numerous registered users across over 40 federal departments and agencies.

name: RadiaPRO Generative Artificial Intelligence Platform (Pilot)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description:
RadiaPRO is a planned enterprise platform by ISED to provide employees with advanced generative artificial intelligence tools and improve business process efficiency. Hosted in the department’s Protected B-certified cloud, it will support interaction with LLMs and agents hosted by Shared Services Canada. RadiaPRO will integrate with internal knowledge bases and, in future, systems like SharePoint and GCdocs. It will offer summarisation, drafting, translation, code assistance, data analysis, and content generation. Users can also design automated workflows. The goal is to reduce repetitive tasks, boost productivity, and explore safe, responsible AI adoption in departmental operations. The platform is planned to be certified for use with information up to Protected B.
RadiaPRO will use a combination of open-source and proprietary components. The platform is primarily built on the LibreChat open-source framework, extended with custom integrations and enhancements for intelligent agents, knowledge base connectivity, and departmental system integration. It will provide access to various proprietary models and services hosted by Share Services Canada or other secure services.
capabilities: Provide secure document summarization, question answering, document drafting, translation, data extraction including tables, coding assistance, file uploads, knowledgebase integration, custom presets, and multi-model side-by-side response comparisons—within a Protected B-certified environment.
data_sources: Inputs during use may include a mix of user-provided public or sensitive information (i.e., protected information) such as documents, text, or data.
results: RadiaPRO will streamline routine tasks for employees of Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada by enabling faster document analysis, drafting, translation, coding, and data extraction. This secure enterprise application will allow the use of large language models and agent-based capabilities with sensitive information, up to Protected B, reducing manual workload, improving accuracy, and enhancing productivity.

name: DesignVision
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Artificial intelligence-enabled system uses computer vision, deep learning algorithm and image recognition software to search tens of millions of existing design applications and registrations world-wide against newly-filed designs in mere seconds instead of having people to visually inspect thousands of designs manually. Since 2022, the system has increased efficiency and quality of examination, while reducing processing times as well as the need for manual labour intensive visual inspection.
capabilities: Image recognition, similarity ranking, pattern detection.
data_sources: Collective industrial design databases from 80 international intellectual property offices.
results: Enables rapid and accurate comparison of designs, reducing manual workload, improving examination quality, and accelerating processing times.

name: Clean Technology Data Strategy Administrative Data Collection
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The Clean Growth Hub leads the administrative data pillar of the Clean Technology Data Strategy. Its goal is to track federal investments in clean technology to inform and support federal programs. Currently, data is collected annually from multiple programs, which is time-consuming and creates reporting burden. To address this, the Hub is using artificial intelligence, specifically a machine learning model, to analyse proactively disclosed grants and contributions, identify clean technology projects, and classify them by subsector. The model was built using free, open-source software and trained on historical data manually gathered in previous years. This approach aims to improve efficiency, reduce burden, and provide timely insights for policy and program development.
capabilities: The system uses machine learning to analyse grant and contribution data, identify clean technology projects, and classify them by subsector. It applies unsupervised learning to detect patterns and groupings in text data, improving accuracy and reducing manual effort.
data_sources: The system uses data from the proactive disclosure of grants and contributions published by the GC. This includes publicly available records of federal funding provided to projects and organisations. Historical datasets compiled manually in previous years were also used to train the model.
results: The implementation has produced a more accurate, timely and complete dataset, reducing manual reporting burden and enabling faster analysis. Using publicly available proactive disclosure data allows the creation of new products that highlight individual clean technology projects, improving transparency and insight.

name: Business Benefits Finder Daily Web Crawler and Daily Web Scraper
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The Daily Web Crawler and Daily Web Scraper are artificial intelligence-enabled tools designed to automate the discovery and extraction of information on government business-support programs at both federal and provincial levels for the Business Benefits Finder. The business problem was the manual, time-consuming process of identifying and updating thousands of program entries. These tools use machine learning and natural language processing to continuously scan official websites, extract relevant program details, and feed structured data into a system for officers to review before uploading to the Business Benefits Finder. The objective is to improve accuracy, timeliness, and comprehensiveness of program listings, reduce manual workload, and ensure Canadian businesses have up-to-date access to funding and support opportunities.
capabilities: Automates discovery and extraction of federal and provincial business-support programmes using artificial intelligence-driven web crawling and scraping, ensuring timely and accurate updates to the Innovation Canada Business Benefits Finder.
data_sources: Public government websites (federal and provincial) containing relevant program information.
results: Updates the Business Benefits Finder in near real time so businesses and innovators can quickly access accurate programme information. Reduces search and update time, improves efficiency, and streamlines how the Government of Canada shares funding and support information.

name: Recognized Technician Monitoring Program (Pilot)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Includes multiple modules, of which the recognized technician monitoring module is primary. Collects qualitative information about service providers as well as the individual technicians who work for them, then assigns risk scores based on the collected data. Risk scores are then supplied to a model to ascertain the amount of monitoring appropriate for each organization and technician. Other modules are attached to this program which (for example) supply recommended monitoring dates for technicians based on risk calculated from previous performance history.
capabilities: Collects performance data of organizations and technicians to model risk and focus oversight on outliers that represent areas of concern. Creates per-technician profiles to recommend increased evaluation frequency of technicians. Data collected during pilot period will be used to construct predictive models.
data_sources: Inspections data collected by both Measurement Canada as well as authorized service providers delegated by Government of Canada, internally collected qualitative performance data (through web forms).
results: Out of pilot phase, expected to deliver predictive models and improved understanding of risk factors in the marketplace. Expected to improve efficiency of inspection teams by enabling them to target areas of high concern.

name: Executive Correspondance Workflow Automation Tool
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The Executive Correspondence Workflow Automation Tool is an artificial intelligence-enabled application developed by Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada to semi-automate the generation of bilingual synopses of ministerial emails. The business problem was the high operational cost and inefficiency of manually summarising and translating over 5,500 emails annually, which led to delays and inconsistent outputs. The tool uses large language models to generate summaries in both English and French, maintaining a consistent format and tone. It also supports categorisation and routing to the appropriate sector. Human review is retained to ensure quality and mitigate risks. The objective is to improve productivity, reduce manual workload, and enhance the accuracy and timeliness of executive correspondence processing.
capabilities: Provides a web-based interface where users input email text, select opening phrases and summary length. The system detects language, summarises content, and generates bilingual summaries in English and French for consistency and efficiency.
data_sources: Text from emails to ministers submitted through the departmental correspondence system.
results: Expected to process up to 5,500 emails annually. Reduces manual effort, speeds tasking, and improves timeliness of public responses. Enhances operational efficiency for the business unit, saving an estimated 24 business days per year.

name: ParlBrief
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: ParlBrief is an artificial intelligence-enabled application to automate the transcription and summarisation of bilingual parliamentary committee meetings. The business problem prompting its development was the requirement for parliamentary affairs units to deliver summaries to the Privy Council Office within three hours of meeting end, resulting in high overtime costs and staff burnout. Off-the-shelf tools failed to meet business requirements due to meeting length and bilingual content. ParlBrief uses a combination of proprietary and open-source language models to transcribe audio, translate content, generate summaries, and assess tone. The objective is to reduce manual workload, improve timeliness and accuracy of summaries, and enhance employee well-being across departments.
capabilities: Uses artificial intelligence with speech-to-text, machine translation, and natural language generation models to transcribe audio, translate content, and produce structured bilingual summaries of parliamentary committee meetings.
data_sources: Notices of parliamentary committee meetings from the House of Commons website (ourcommons.ca) and video recordings from ParlVU (parlvu.parl.gc.ca).
results: Generates accurate transcripts and summaries of parliamentary committee meetings within minutes. Reduces manual transcription and translation effort, reducing time, cost and improving timeliness of reporting to senior officials, and supports compliance with parliamentary reporting requirements.

name: Debtor Detection Anomaly System
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Uses artificial intelligence to identify anomalies in estate filings submitted to the Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy. It supports analysts in assessing the integrity of the insolvency system by complementing existing manual selection processes, random Debtor Compliance reviews, referrals from Licensed Insolvency Trustees, and public complaints. The system is not an automated decision-making tool and does not replace human judgment. It serves as an input to improve risk-based oversight and could be adapted for other anomaly detection use cases.
capabilities: Uses unsupervised machine learning to identify high-risk insolvency files for manual review, improving compliance efficiency.
data_sources: Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy insolvency data.
results: Provides compliance risk rankings and identifies risk attributes in estate filings. These outputs are used by the Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy compliance analysts to prioritise and determine whether further investigation is required.

name: Ombot
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Ombot is an artificial intelligence-enabled virtual assistant on Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada's intranet that provides confidential access to information about the Ombuds Office. It was developed to address employee discomfort and delays in accessing support services, especially in sensitive situations. The business problem was the lack of a private, user-friendly channel for employees to explore Ombuds services without fear of exposure. Ombot uses generative artificial intelligence to deliver conversational guidance, with safeguards and governance measures in place to ensure privacy, safety, and responsible use. The objective is to increase employee trust, reduce barriers to support, and enable scalable deployment across departments through a “bot-in-a-box” model.
capabilities: A bilingual chatbot using natural language processing and generative artificial intelligence to deliver accurate, confidential, real-time answers about Ombuds Office services. Responses are sourced from a controlled knowledge base with safeguards for sensitive queries.
data_sources: Knowledge base of unstructured text containing information about Ombuds Office services and role.
results: Improves access to Ombuds Office services by automating responses to recurring questions previously handled by email. Saves about eight business days annually, reduces manual effort, and ensures faster, consistent, and more accessible well-being and conflict resolution services for employees.

name: Automated Information Extraction of Spectrum Licence Conditions
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The system automatically extracts spectrum licence conditions from regulatory documents and presents them in a structured, machine-readable format. This approach addresses the business problem of manual review, which is time-consuming, error-prone, and limits timely access to critical information for clients in the Spectrum and Telecommunications Sector. The objective is to improve efficiency, accuracy, and accessibility by enabling automated spectrum analytics and by supporting evidence-based decision-making.
capabilities: Generative artificial intelligence system that extracts, organises, and structures regulatory and technical rules from sector websites and unstructured documents using large language models and retrieval-augmented generation for accurate, structured outputs.
data_sources: Unstructured spectrum licencing documents from the Spectrum and Telecommunications Sector, sourced from publicly available regulatory records and official publications.
results: Delivers automated, accurate extraction and structuring of regulatory and technical rules from diverse unstructured sources, providing stakeholders with faster, easier access to relevant information. Improves efficiency, reduces manual effort, and supports compliance and policy development.

name: Detection and Labelling of Anomalies in Spectrum Licence Site Data
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Use machine learning to detect and label errors or anomalies in the spectrum licence site data submitted by Wireless Service Providers. Manual anomaly detection is slow, inconsistent, and resource-intensive, creating risks for compliance and spectrum management. The objective is to automate anomaly identification, improve data quality, and enable timely, accurate insights for planning and regulatory oversight.
capabilities: Uses machine learning to detect and label anomalies in spectrum licence site data submitted by Internet Service Providers, improving accuracy, consistency, and efficiency in data validation for spectrum management and compliance.
data_sources: Spectrum licence site data submitted by Internet Service Providers, sourced from Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada’s Spectrum Management System and other publicly available regulatory datasets.
results: Creates a positive feedback loop by detecting anomalies and providing insights that help Internet Service Providers improve the accuracy of site data submissions over time. Also, allows the regulator to identify and filter low-quality information.  This enhances data quality, supports spectrum licence compliance, and strengthens planning and regulatory oversight.

name: Artificial Intelligence-based Web Accessibility Review and Enhancement (AWARE) (Pilot)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Automate and optimize web publishing workflows for greater efficiency and consistency; generate Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada-compliant HTML5 content and enhance web accessibility standards.
capabilities: Code conversion and cleaning, generating compliant HTML5 content, JSON, MathML, and JavaScript. Handles multi-format content; facilitates integration with content management systems like Drupal; optimizes programming language development and language translation.
data_sources: Word documents, PDF files, HTML, Excel, CSV, and image files related to web content.
results: Streamlines web publishing workflows, improves coding efficiency and consistency, enhances accessibility standards, supports faster web publications, and demonstrates practical application of artificial intelligence in real-world challenges.

name: Qualitative Analysis of Public Opinion (Pilot)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: System used to analyse structured and semi-structured data from public opinion research responses. The system uses large language models to increase efficiency and reduce bias in qualitative analysis of large files, reducing the need for a second analyst. This addresses the challenge of resource-intensive manual analysis and supports timely, consistent insights for decision-making.
capabilities: Applies natural language processing and large language models to analyse structured and semi-structured data, improving speed and consistency of qualitative analysis.
data_sources: Public opinion research responses and related datasets, including Library and Archives studies.
results: Expected to enable faster, more consistent qualitative analysis of public opinion research, reducing resource requirements and improving efficiency for internal and partner use.

name: Competition Artificial Intelligence Secure System (COMPASS)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: A secure, Protected B compliant generative artificial intelligence platform designed to support competition enforcement and promotion. It addresses the challenge of analysing large volumes of sensitive and confidential information efficiently, which previously required significant manual effort. By leveraging large language models, the platform enhances analytical capabilities, enabling faster identification of patterns, trends, and insights in complex investigations. It processes public and confidential input from consultations and market studies, builds searchable knowledge bases from sensitive case documents and legal texts, and monitors competition-related developments from digital sources. These capabilities support efficient investigations, legal analysis, and advocacy. The objective is to improve decision-making, increase operational efficiency, and maintain the highest standards of data security and confidentiality.
capabilities: Processes sensitive data securely, uses large language models for advanced text analysis, summarisation, and pattern detection.
data_sources: Internal data.
results: The intended result is to establish a secure framework for Protected B compliant generative artificial intelligence technologies. This framework will enable data scientists to safely leverage advanced analytical tools to support enforcement teams, improving efficiency, insight generation, and decision-making in complex investigations.

name: Intelligent System for Content Analysis of Names (ISCAN)
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: An internal tool developed by Corporations Canada to assist with post-filing reviews of Individuals with Significant Control filings. It uses machine learning to flag potentially inappropriate, non-genuine, or offensive names for human review. The objective is to improve operational efficiency and accuracy in maintaining data integrity while ensuring compliance with legal requirements. The system does not make administrative decisions; all flagged cases are reviewed by staff.
capabilities: Uses natural language processing and machine learning to detect anomalies or inappropriate content in Individuals with Significant Control name fields and flag them for human review.
data_sources: Internal Corporations Canada Individuals with Significant Control filings dataset, structured name fields.
results: Increased efficiency and accuracy in screening Individuals with Significant Control filings, reduced manual review workload, and improved compliance with data integrity standards.

name: Cyber Threat Hunting
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: To accelerate the creation of threat hunting queries for detecting cyber threats within our environment, this system leverages generative artificial intelligence tools, such as Anthropic Claude and Copilot. These tools assist in developing Kusto Query Language queries that identify potential threats in security logs. The primary objective is to reduce the time and complexity involved in writing advanced queries for threat hunting, particularly when correlating data across multiple sources.
capabilities: Leverages generative artificial intelligence tools and public web data to develop Kusto Querry Language queries based on prompts provided by a user.
data_sources: Public data available on the internet for query generation and internal audit logs collected via Security Information and Event Management for execution of generated queries.
results: Accelerates the development of complex queries for searching audit logs in Security Information and Event Management systems, particularly when correlation across multiple data sources is required, improving threat detection speed, reducing analyst workload, and enhancing response times.

name: Entity and User Behavior Analytics
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The Entity and User Behavior Analytics system uses artificial intelligence to monitor and analyse patterns of user and entity activity within the department’s information technology environment. The objective is to detect abnormal or suspicious behaviour that may indicate cybersecurity threats, insider risks, or compromised accounts. The system leverages machine learning and large language models to identify anomalies and present visual trends over time, enabling proactive threat detection and improved security posture.
capabilities: Detects anomalies in user and entity behaviour using machine learning and large language models, with visual dashboards for trend analysis and security alerts.
data_sources: System logs, network activity data, and security event data from internal information technology infrastructure.
results: Enhanced cybersecurity through early detection of abnormal behaviour, reducing risk of data breaches and improving incident response times.

name: Debt Questionnaire
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: Uses artificial intelligence to analyse historical bankruptcy and insolvency data and compare it with information provided by Canadians considering debt relief. The business problem was the lack of accessible, data-driven guidance for individuals facing financial distress. The system identifies patterns from previous insolvency filings to suggest what type of insolvency others with similar financial profiles have chosen. It is a decision-support tool, not an automated decision-maker, allowing users to consider guidance when making informed choices.
capabilities: Applies classical machine learning to pre-screen financial distress and offer tailored debt relief options based on historical insolvency data.
data_sources: Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy insolvency data.
results: Compares information provided by Canadians in financial distress with historical insolvency data to show the percentage of similar cases for each insolvency option. Displays these percentages based on the user’s input to help inform their decision. Provides data-driven guidance to help users make informed decisions without automating the choice.

name: NUANS Business Name Submission Prediction and Scoring Filings Improvement Project
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: A planned system to predict the likelihood of business name registration requests being accepted across jurisdictions.
capabilities: To be determined.
data_sources: To be determined.
results: Reduce the need for Canadian businesses and entrepreneurs to resubmit corporation name applications, improving client service, reducing government examiner workload, and increasing efficiency in assessing business name requests.​

name: Canada Business App
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The Canada Business App, launched in June 2019 on Apple App Store and Google Play, helps Canadian business owners access federal, provincial, and territorial services for starting and growing businesses. Artificial intelligence will soon be integrated to provide personalised service recommendations based on business profiles. The objective is to improve navigation of thousands of resources by matching users to relevant programs and services using curated, unclassified datasets.
capabilities: Personalised recommendations using large language models to match businesses with relevant government services and programmes.
data_sources: Curated, unclassified datasets related to financing, innovation, licensing, permits, and government marketing initiatives.
results: Improved user experience through tailored guidance, faster access to relevant services, and better support for Canadian business growth.

name: BizPal
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: BizPaL is an online tool that helps businesses identify the permits and licences required from all levels of government, reducing the time and effort needed to understand compliance obligations. The database currently includes approximately 1,200 permits and licences. Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada is planning to integrate artificial intelligence, including machine learning and advanced data visualisation, to address the challenge of navigating complex and fragmented regulatory information across federal, provincial and territorial jurisdictions. The objective is to improve accuracy, efficiency and user experience by providing businesses with clearer, more tailored guidance on regulatory requirements. BizPaL also uses generative artificial intelligence to produce simplified summaries of permits, licences and legislative content, which are reviewed and edited by the BizPaL content team to ensure clarity and accuracy.
capabilities: The system plans to use artificial intelligence to classify and match permits and licences, extract key regulatory details, and generate tailored recommendations. It applies machine learning for pattern recognition and advanced data visualisation to improve navigation and understanding of compliance requirements.
data_sources: Notices of parliamentary committee meetings from the House of Commons website (ourcommons.ca) and video recordings from ParlVU (parlvu.parl.gc.ca).
results: Enhances search by interpreting natural language and mapping it to regulatory terms, bridging business and legal language. Generates simplified summaries of permits, licences and legislation, improving clarity and reducing complexity for businesses.

name: Weights and Measures Marketplace Monitoring Algorithm
department: Innovation, Science and Economic Development Canada
description: The algorithm supports Measurement Canada in determining where and when inspections should occur to monitor compliance with the Weights and Measures Act. It uses predictive analytics to identify high-risk areas and overdue devices, improving efficiency and fairness in enforcement.
capabilities: Machine learning-based predictive analytics to assess non-compliance risk and inform inspection scheduling.
data_sources: Historic inspection records and compliance data from Measurement Canada systems.
results: Marketplace monitoring is more risk-focused and informed by predictive analysis, improving resource allocation and compliance outcomes.

name: AI textual analysis tools
description: Pilot project to categorize a sample of 25,000 digital archival files
capabilities: Automatic document classification, metadata creation, information architecture integration.
data_sources: 25,000 digital archival files
results: Capability proven viable for future pilots and projects.

name: Transkribus Transcription: Canadian Newspapers Index & Order-in-Council Registers (1925 to 1940)
description: Pilot transcription projects using Transkribus AI model to improve access to historical records: (1) Index of Canadian Newspapers and (2) Order-in-Council Registers (1925 to 1940). Both projects aim to digitize and transcribe records for improved access and digital storage. Developed by LAC in collaboration with READ-COOP (Transkribus, originating from EU-funded READ project, University of Innsbruck)
capabilities: Handwritten and printed text transcription using AI models; Intelligent Character Recognition (ICR) and Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR) developed by READ-COOP.

capabilities: Metadata enrichment
data_sources: Sample of 1000 digitized government publications
results: Capability proven viable for future pilots and projects.

name: Canada Gazette Immigration Records  AWS Textract Project
description: Use AWS Textract to extract and index immigration information from 11,231 pages of the Canada Gazette for genealogy research. Developed by LAC using AWS Textract with ElasticSearch indexing.
capabilities: Optical Character Recognition (OCR) for structured documents; text extraction from tables; ElasticSearch indexing for searchability.
data_sources: Canada Gazette immigration records (11,231 pages)
results: Extracted immigration data from 11,231 pages of Canada Gazette at a cost of $170.45 USD using AWS Textract; cleaned and added to ElasticSearch database for enhanced genealogical search.

name: CANChat Generative AI Chatbot LLM (Shared Services Canada with LAC training data)
description: Generative AI chatbot for unclassified government work, trained on Canadian data (including 50 TB from LAC Government of Canada Web Archive) to enhance employee productivity, sovereignty, and digital independence. Shared Services Canada (CANChat initiative) with training data support from LAC.
capabilities: Large Language Models (LLMs); generative AI for text drafting, research support, knowledge management; trained on Canadian sovereign data hosted in Canadian data centres.

results: Trained sovereign generative AI chatbot with Canadian-hosted LLMs; over 50 TB of GC web data used; supported productivity use cases (drafting, research); LAC contributing white papers on AI & preservation  and organizing IIPC AI session in 2026.

name: RG10 Transcription (ICR/LLM with Transkribus)
description: Improve access to Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development historical records (RG10) via transcription of ~6 million pages, relevant to Indigenous history. Developed by LAC and CRKN (Canadian Research Knowledge Network) in collaboration with READ-COOP (Transkribus, originating from EU-funded READ project, University of Innsbruck)
capabilities: Intelligent Character Recognition (ICR) and Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR) using machine learning and large language models, developed by READ-COOP
data_sources: RG10 Collection: ~6 million pages of Department of Indian Affairs and Northern Development historical records
results: ICR work anticipated to process 0.5-1.5 million pages by March 2023; estimated throughput 1 million pages per month; full RG10 collection ~5-6 million pages.

name: Automated Document Classification for Network Shared Drives (NSD) to GCdocs
description: Automatically classify ~10 million documents from the former LAC Network Shared Drives (NSD) and eliminate ROT (Redundant, Obsolete, Trivial) information. Developed via RFP process
capabilities: Automatic document classification, metadata creation, information architecture integration
data_sources: Documents from LAC Network Shared Drives (NSD)
results: 3.5 million documents moved and classified into GCdocs with new metadata; links left in NSD; ROT eliminated; multiple presentations delivered across GC and at conferences.

name: Census 1931 Index (HTR with Ancestry and FamilySearch)
description: Create a full index of the 1931 Canadian Census (~10 million names) using handwriting recognition technology and AI for transcription. Developed by Ancestry (proprietary HTR/AI) in partnership with FamilySearch; LAC provided digitized preservation assets
capabilities: Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR), AI-based transcription of census data
data_sources: 1931 Canadian Census images (~230,000 images, ~10 million names)
results: Full searchable index of 1931 Canadian Census made available online via LAC Census Search; preservation assets securely stored at Preservation Centre and across Canada.

To accurately assess positions and predict human behaviour through a series of statistical techniques against randomized, controlled samples of populations constructed through social media.

description: A chatbot to quickly search through DND/CAF policy documents.
capabilities: Chatbot to provide answers on Policy documents
data_sources: DND/CAF Policy documents publicly available

description: An AI-based tool to identify and redact sensitive information from documents before release.
capabilities: This tool uses multi AI models and Human in the loop to help with ATIP requests
data_sources: In development the tool uses non production documents and only publicly available documents. Only In prodcution this tool will be  Pro B MM and will use personal information.

description: A financial forecasting tool to help financial comptrollers forecast in-year budget expenditures.
capabilities: This AI tool uses previous years financial information to predict relavant information and help ADM (Fin) officers

capabilities: This AI tool will use multiple AI models to translate text and voice documents.

description: AI classifies data per security and retention policies, reducing compliance risks.

We use and have used machine learning processes in all 3 projects since 2019.
