name: Virtual semiconductor fabrication model
description: NRC in collaboration with McGill University has devised a digital solution to reduce the impact of fabrication imperfections on semiconductor component's optical performance. This approach is a machine learning-based model to predict fabrication outcomes of design layouts. Designers can conduct virtual trials on the model, ensure that clients'expectations are met and collect useful data before sending their designs to the manufacturer.
capabilities: Deep learning
data_sources: Internal research data. Fabrication and imaging from Applied Nanotools Inc.
results: A machine learning-based model to predict fabrication outcomes of design layouts

name: Monitoring ocean health and carbon sequestration
description: NRC's Ocean program and a research team from the University of Victoria have partnered  to monitor ocean health and its capacity for carbon sequestration using a novel suite of sensors, machine learning and a remotely operated vehicle (ROV). The project also includes a cybersecurity component to assess vulnerabilities in the ROV's sensor network to protect data privacy.
capabilities: The project uses a transformer-based machine learning model pre-trained on historical publicly available data from Ocean Networks Canada to predict chlorophyll concentrations. This model helps researchers assess the health of marine ecosystems and their capacity for carbon uptake.
data_sources: Publicly available data
results: This model helps researchers assess the health of marine ecosystems and their capacity for carbon uptake.

name: Monitoring nutritional intake in older adults
description: Tracking eating patterns helps detect possible dietary changes to improve nutrition and extend lifespan. This is particularly important for older adults looking to prevent or manage dementia, continue to live well and age in place. This new AI research tool was designed to provide higher accuracy, simplify the monitoring process and lighten the load of self-reporting.
results: The team's model for predicting calories, mass, protein, fat and carbohydrates from images of a meal showed a 25.5% improvement over the current state-of-the-art model, leading to much greater accuracy in dietary estimation.

name: Enhance Transportation Infrastructure Resiliency through Bridge Monitoring
description: Canada has more than 50,000 publicly owned bridges. Many are reaching the end of their lifespan and 11% are reported to be in poor or very poor condition. While the design life of a bridge is generally 50 to 75 years, they can safely last longer with good monitoring and timely maintenance, which requires a significant public investment. The National Research Council of Canada's AI for Logistics program is addressing these challenges together with experts from Housing, Infrastructure and Communities Canada, Esri Canada and the University of Manitoba. They are developing improved methods for life-long monitoring of infrastructure conditions and decision support for maintenance investment by studying a highway bridge in Manitoba.  This will enhance the potential for remote bridge monitoring and reduce physical and economic risks related to bridge failure.
capabilities: When completed, the project will provide an AI-based bridge health predictor that governments could use to support decision-makers in their operation and investment in bridge maintenance, renewal or replacement.
results: This will enhance the potential for remote bridge monitoring and reduce physical and economic risks related to bridge failure.

name: AI planner for truck routes
description: The National Research Council of Canada (NRC), the University of Calgary, the City of Calgary and 2 of Canada’s largest transportation companies have worked together to develop new smart AI-driven tools for truck-route planning. By anticipating traffic patterns, the new software enables planners to choose the most effective routes, which is particularly helpful in extreme weather conditions.
data_sources: Client data
results: Using the software reduces the travelling distance and number of vehicles needed to deliver goods from depots to destinations. The new software enables planners to choose the most effective routes, which is particularly helpful in extreme weather conditions. It also has a significant beneficial impact on finances and the environment, since each minute of travel time saved in a transport truck can be worth hundreds of dollars and reductions in CO2 emissions.

name: AI for molecule discovery
description: Molecule discovery is at the root of new health and other scientific discoveries, but the process of identifying the molecules needed for a specific cause is often slow and very costly. Artificial intelligence (AI) offers a faster, less expensive way of sorting through the large amount of data and huge candidate space to determine which molecules are the best fit. Using AI, the NRC and collaborators from Mila, McGill, and SickKids are currently accelerating the process of discovering molecules that can be used in healthcare and clean energy applications, while reducing costs. The project also focuses on molecule identification for developing green materials for clean energy, and on environmental protection, such as innovative battery technology to power electric vehicles or better methods for carbon capture and storage.
results: Accelerating the process of discovering molecules that can be used in healthcare and clean energy applications, while reducing costs

name: Drone detection
description: As their numbers surge, uncrewed aerial systems (UASs), commonly known as drones, will pose more hazards than ever to privacy, security, lives, homes and infrastructure. Over the past 4 years, an R&D team of engineers and scientists from the NRC's Digital Technologies Research Centre and the DRDC have developed an innovative technological solution for passively spotting drones in cluttered settings. It incorporates AI to accurately detect, track and characterize drones on the basis of the signal generated by their rotating propellers rather than by using an image bank. This method generates very few false alarms and accurately detects low-flying drones that use topography to evade discovery.
results: AI to accurately detect, track and characterize drones

name: Oxygen predictor in the water of North Atlantic estuary ecosystems
description: NRC scientists are using machine learning to predict dissolved oxygen levels in Atlantic estuaries, a key indicator of water quality. This AI-driven approach can forecast low-oxygen events days in advance, even in highly degraded sites, and outperforms traditional deep learning methods. By anticipating problems like eutrophication and harmful algal blooms, the method provides valuable insights for environmental managers, helping them protect marine biodiversity, support aquaculture, and maintain healthy coastal ecosystems.
results: Predict dissolved oxygen levels in Atlantic estuaries

name: YeastNet
description: Developed in collaboration with UOttawa. Accurate and efficient segmentation of live-cell images is critical in maximizing data extraction and knowledge generation from high-throughput biology experiments. YeastNet enables accurate automatic segmentation and tracking of yeast cells in biomedical applications. Prototype developed and published.
data_sources: Microscope images
results: YeastNet enables accurate automatic segmentation and tracking of yeast cells in biomedical applications.

name: QuaLC
description: Developed in collaboration with Uottawa. Digital Shadow of Liquid Chromatography system for providing warning about experiment problems. Prototype developed and in preparation for publication and hosting on complimet.ca.
data_sources: Liquid chromatography pressure profile
results: AI algorithms trained on the shadow's historical data providing warning about experiment problems.

name: AI-based, live visual bridge inspection by drone system
description: The AI automatically detects surface defects, identify them and highlight them in an augmented reality that is provided to the inspectors. The objectives are to make bridge inspections safer, cheaper and faster by combining the benefits of drone technology and AI along with other advanced digital technologies. Currently at proof of concept.
data_sources: CODEBRIM Dataset
results: Assistant to the bridge inspectors. The objectives are to make bridge inspections safer, cheaper and faster.

name: Global Public Health Intelligence Network (GPHIN)
description: GPHIN's mission is to be an indispensable source of early warning for potential public health threats worldwide including chemical, biological, radiological and nuclear (CBRN). Because time is of the essence, the goal is to use leading-edge communications technology and automated processes on a real-time 24/7 basis complemented by human analysis to monitor media sources worldwide and provide organized, relevant information to users allowing them to respond to potential health threats in a timely manner.
capabilities: Translation, relevance scoring, geographic resolution and mapping, clustering, time series change point detection, anomaly detection, near duplicate detection, categorization
data_sources: News from Dow Jones Factiva; RSS news feeds
results: Substantially lower costs, higher quality output, and higher data volume than previous vendor-delivered system.

name: Food Inspection Environment Scanning Canada (FIESCA)
description: A platform to surveil agricultural trade publications in countries from which Canada imports food in order to detect e.g. pesticides newly authorized in foreign countries so that Canada can preemptively increase residual testing at the border.
capabilities: Translation, relevance scoring, geographic resolution and mapping, near duplicate detection, categorization
data_sources: News from Dow Jones Factiva; RSS news feeds
results: Substantially increased amount of data available to analysts, particularly when mining data published in other languages (e.g. Spanish language trade publications in Mexico).

name: Global Situational Surveillance Environment (GLOSSE)
description: A platform to surveil local news media overseas to assist international Watch Offices with response to local crises, e.g. quickly determine the most suitable evacuation countries/routes for Canadians overseas when conflict occurs.
capabilities: Translation, relevance scoring, geographic resolution and mapping, near duplicate detection, categorization
data_sources: News from Dow Jones Factiva; RSS news feeds
results: Decreased time to respond to rapidly evolving events overseas.

name: ExaCT
description: ExaCT is an automatic information extraction system  that assists medical researchers and clinicians with locating and extracting key characteristics of randomized controlled trials from full-text journal articles. Clinical trials are one of the most important sources of evidence for guiding evidence-based practice and the design of new trials. However, most of this information is available only in free text, which is labour intensive to process manually for systematic reviews, meta-analyses, and other evidence synthesis studies. ExaCT is designed to partially automate and speed up this process.
capabilities: Information extraction
data_sources: Scientific Journal Article
results: Decreased time to systematic literature reviews.

name: Parliamentary Machine Translation
description: The National Research Council Digital Technologies Research Centre, in collaboration with the Translation Bureau, has developed domain-specific neural machine translation systems for the use of House of Commons and Senate translators.
capabilities: Machine translation
data_sources: Past human translator outputs
results: User studies reveal increasing adoption and positive reviews about the higher precision of the domain-specific translation.

name: EveryVoice TTS

It is used to add realistic pronunciation recordings to text learning materials like dictionaries and verb conjugation references.

results: Enthusiastic initial responses from teachers and linguists.

name: Surrogate-assisted optimization of a U-shaped actuator MEMS design
description: The system is to design and optimize an electromagnetic actuator for the Low-Voltage Deformable Mirror, aimed at compensating disturbed optical wavefronts caused by atmospheric turbulence applicable in optical communications and astronomical observations. We developed an AI algorithm, Surrogate-Assisted Multi-Objective Optimization, to identify more accurate optimal designs even in cases where data from simulations and prototype fabrication are very limited. It demonstrates the feasibility of this AI-based approach for electromagnetic MEMS actuators and electrostatic and thermal MEMS device.
capabilities: Machine learning, Optimizaiton
data_sources: Generated from the COMSOL simulation
results: This accelerated design and optimization helped developing novel ideas about further miniaturization of electromagnetic MEMS architecture, leading to the concept of fabricating micro-magnets on silicon wafers directly using additive manufacturing (i.e. cold spray and/or binder jet).

name: Hydrogen Leakage Monitor
description: Hydrogen leakage is a serious safety risk for operation of hydrogen refueling stations. The system is developed to monitor the hydrogen leakage in real-time on stations. We developed a holistic method for calculating the hydrogen loss based on streaming data of hydrogen produced and filled.
capabilities: A portal for hydrogen loss monitoring is developed. It generates daily, weekly, and monthly hydrogen loss statistics. It monitors the overall station operational status and evaluating hydrogen losses of different combinations of station operations. Also, it detects the abnormal operation of stations and identifies the source component of hydrogen loss.
data_sources: Real operational data from HTEC
results: HTEC is using the hydrogen loss portal in real operation of hydrogen refueling stations. As a contribution to the research community and industry, an academic paper is published at the International Journal of Hydrogen Energy.

name: AI for novel perovskite discovery and synthesis
description: Perovskite are a class of materials important in several engineeering applications including clean energy technologies. AI can be used to help identify and synthesize novel perovskites with tagarted properties more rapidly and efficiently than traditional trial and error methods.  NRC has developed a pipeline for the discovery of novel perovskites and for the indentification of optimal parameters during ball milling synthesis. This was developed in collaboration with University of Ottawa as part of the AI for Design Challenge Program. Currently in development.
capabilities: Novel perovskite material discovery and synthesis - Generative AI for the discovery and Bayesian Optimization for Synthesis parameters.
data_sources: Public datasets
results: Reduced time to perovskite discovery and synthesis which potentially results in reduction of costs for discovery.

name: AI  for scientific discovery
description: AI is being developed to advance scientific discovery including novel drugs and battery materials.  For example AI for discovery of lithium cathodes for battery applications. For example AI for T-Cell protein editing that can be used for personalized cancer cell therapies.  These applications are being developed with collaborators as part of the AI for Design Challenge program.
results: Enhancement of designs though AI

name: AI-based sea-ice presence forecasting model
description: The system forecasts harbour ice up in the north.  Accurate and timely forecasts of sea ice conditions are crucial for safe shipping operations in the Canadian Arctic and other ice-infested waters. Sea-ice forecasts can be obtained through an optimal combination of sea-ice model output and observational data, in a manner similar to weather forecasting. However, these forecasting systems typically rely on accurate weather forecasting data to drive the sea-ice model, which is not available at high spatial resolution during the advance tactical planning stage. For this reason, seasonal sea ice forecasts are often obtained through statistical means. This Project builds on a prototype system that used artificial intelligence (AI) methods to provide state-of-the-art seasonal forecasts of sea ice conditions in the Canadian Arctic. Codeveloped with University of Waterloo.
capabilities: SIFNET forecast products are now produced on a daily basis and integrated into the existing NRC-OCRE tool CASRAS (Canadian Arctic Shipping Risk Assessment System). CASRAS updates also made available to external stakeholders as of 2023.
results: Safety and shipping / transportation efficiency improvements, enabling related social and health benefits.

name: AI-powered drone system for aerial object detection and collision avoidance
description: Improved AI capabilites for drones (UAV) to operate more safely in complex environments beyond visual line of sight (BVLOS).  This enables UAS platforms such as drones to safely perform inspection, monitoring and modeling of the state of critical infrastructure and superstructures in the BVLOS (beyond visual line of sight) mode. This involves a threat detection and collision avoidance system enabling BVLOS navigation of multiple drones to and around an infrastructure / superstructure target using AI-enabled computer vision and photogrammetry to enable the development of high-precision inspection, mapping and automatic condition assessments.
capabilities: This work addresses three key UAS challenges: BVLOS flight path planning and safe landing, object and intruder detection via on-board electro-optic and radar sensors, and aerial inspection, photogrammetry, and 3D modeling.
data_sources: Real world data captured through over 20 sessions of UAV flight testing in Ottawa, Montreal, Victoria, and Cowichan Territory in Vancouver Island. Synthetic data generated using a combination of in-house UAV simulation software, open-sources and commercial scientific software.
results: Improved technologies for safe Beyond Visual Line of Sight (BVLOS) UAV operation: airspace integration in complex or crowded airspace and collision avoidance, and aerial inspection of infrastructrure with onboard UAV sensors.

name: AI-enabled system for multi-modal data alignment/cross-calibration for driver assistance (prediction)
description: System enables driver movements (gaze) to be aligned with changes in the external environment to permit AI assistance to the driver to improve safety.  It is an AI-based driver intentionality predictor capable of augmenting and enhancing typical advanced driver assistance systems (ADAS) by broadening their time horizon. In the long term, having models that predict driver intentionality and actions can provide additional information to an ADAS that can be used to alert the driver or take action to ensure the safety of the vehicle and driver or avoid likely accident scenarios. Co-developed with the University of Western Ontario.
results: Improved driver-assistance technologies and driving safety.

name: AI for signal detection of emerging technologies
description: Articles in scientific publications often contain hints about important emerging technologies, but signals that indicate the next big risk to national and international security are often subtle. The challenge is to detect these weak signals and assess their possible impacts on future security, then use that intelligence to reinforce defence. For the past decade, the NRC and DRDC have used scientometrics, the science of measuring and analyzing scholarly literature, to track, measure and identify technology trends in different scientific fields. The NRC, DRDC and international allies and partners have prototyped an ingenious AI solution that simplifies and improves both weak-signal detection and monitoring of emerging technologies. It also introduces new techniques for predicting the impacts of these technologies and detecting opportunities for innovation.
results: AI solution that simplifies and improves both weak-signal detection and monitoring of emerging technologies. It also introduces new techniques for predicting the impacts of these technologies and detecting opportunities for innovation.

name: Canadian Geospatial Data Infrastructure Geospatial Services Web Harvester
description: Uses ML/AI to automatically identify standards-based geospatial web services (such as Web Map Service (WMS), Web Feature Service (WFS), Web Map Tile Service (WMTS) and Esri Representational State Transfer (REST) services) that provide access to geospatial data. The ML/AI identifies and filters services available for the Arctic and Canadian domain (.ca domain). Purpose of application is to help identify services that are part of the Canadian Geospatial Data Infrastructure (CGDI) and to understand how widely standards-based geospatial web services are being implemented. A similar AI system is also operated to identify the same web services, but only those that provide geospatial data for the Arctic contributing to the Arctic Spatial Data Infrastructure (ArcticSDI).
capabilities: Automatic identification of standards-based geospatial web services for the .ca domain and that provide data for the Arctic.
data_sources: Publicly available Web Map Service (WMS), Web Feature Service (WFS), Web Map Tile Service (WMTS) and Esri Representational State Transfer (REST) services. Services are accessed over the Internet.
results: Identified Web Map Service (WMS), Web Feature Service (WFS), Web Map Tile Service (WMTS) & Esri Representational State Transfer (REST) services available in the .ca domain and services that provide data for the Arctic. Results for the .ca domain are updated weekly and published at https://natural-resources.canada.ca/science-data/science-research/geomatics/geospatial-web-services. Future improvements aim to increase the number of public geospatial web services that can be automatically identified

name: Flood Susceptibility Index
description: Machine learning to create a national map showing how likely a given area is to be affected by flooding.

data_sources: This national map of flood susceptibility or flood prone areas is based on patterns of historic flood event data as predicted by an ensemble machine learning model.

results: AI-enabled processing to render historical air photo usable in modern digital systems at scale, unlocking highly valuable historical data for modern objectives and policy.

name: Automated LiDAR PointCloud Classification
description: Provide a framework to automatically classify buildings, ground, surface water and other features from LiDAR and LiDAR-derived products. The framework contains trained model, documentation, indications to improve models (if required) and knowledge transfer to the production teams.
capabilities: Classify points in LiDAR pointcloud and LiDAR-derived products.
data_sources: Airborne LiDAR across Canada
results: Capacity to classify buildings, ground, surface water and other features from LiDAR and LiDAR-derived products.

name: Canadian Geospatial Foundation Model
description: Development of foundation geospatial model to the Canadian context. Creating a unified, inclusive and more comprehensive frameworks to increase efficiency, operationalization and scalability of all individual geospatial AI solutions.
capabilities: Foundation models are types of AI models that are trained on massive, diverse geospatial EO datasets, mainly in form of imagery but can also be in form of elevation models, geographic coordinates, time tags, spectral information of sensors, descriptive texts, and all other types of attributes attached to EO data.  These models have a representation learning capacity, which simply means these models can learn how to describe data (not to interpret it, just to describe it).
data_sources: Open EO datasets (Sentinel, Landsat) and licenced high-resolution imagery
results: Foundation models are further trained/refined to meet specific downstream requirements, for example, detecting anolomies in ocean shipping corridors, or tracking new housing starts.

description: Apply computational and machine learning methods to develop and design CO2-philic LMWGs by identifying potential building block molecules, constructing molecular models, designing simulation protocols, and conducting molecular simulations to guide and optimize discovery efforts.
capabilities: Develop machine learning models for predicting properties of CO2-philic LMWGs based on their physical, chemical and thermodynamic properties in CO2, and help accelerating material discovery by reducing the need for extensive trial-and-error laboratory experiments.
data_sources: Sources of data to train are obtained from advanced molecular modeling simulations; inputs for the AI/ML system may include molecular structures, calculated molecular properties, and experimentally measured properties, if available.

name: AI tool for CFD modelling post-processing
description: This study shows how artificial intelligence (AI) can make industrial decarbonization research faster, smarter, and more effective. Specifically, we applied AI to analyze simulations of electric arc furnaces (EAFs), where biomass-derived carbon particles are injected to reduce carbon emissions in steel production. Traditional simulation analysis relies heavily on human interpretation of complex data, which can miss hidden patterns. By using AI techniques, we were able to uncover these patterns and gain a deeper, data-driven understanding of how particles behave inside the furnace.
data_sources: Data is generated by NRCan
results: Aids in computational fluid dynamic (CFD) data analysis.

results: Improvement of the overall user experience in GEO.ca. The semantic search system not only capture the intent behind search queries but also understand the context of the search.  This state-of-the-art approach significantly enhance search accuracy and user experience on the GEO.ca platform.

name: Self-hosted LLM framework
description: Looking for a framework through which self-hosted LLMs could be deployed on premises, the department settled on the open-source Ollama solution, which allows the use of powerful AI models for experimentation, research and development work without the data processing taking place outside the organization.  The Ollama framework allows specialists within the organization to use the latest self-hosted models, while running the experiments required to develop concepts into potential solutions for the organization.

name: Copilot
description: Copilot (and its premium offering M365 Copilot) is a general-purpose generative AI solution offered to GC departments.  The PSC piloted its implementation in late 2024/early 2025, then used the lessons from this pilot to guide the organization in its use of the platform throughout 2025, for instance, by reinforcing the FASTER principles in its use and referencing the Guide on the use of Generative AI published by TBS.  Mid-2025 usage of Copilot is focused on personal productivity -- text generation, text editing, image generation, text summarization and translation.)  Over the next year, the PSC hopes to focus on a more enterprise-level use of Copilot through complex shared prompts and Copilot agents providing specialized chatbot capabilities from a selected corpus of documentation.
capabilities: Copilot provides general-purpose generative AI capabilities of PSC employees, including text generation, text editing, document summarization and image generation.

results: Provide a general-purpose foundation for enterprise exploration of LLM capabilities, including moving from personal productivity (text generation and editing) to a deliberate enterprise-grade usage of LLM, for instance in using structured knowledge bases for domain-specific agents, or using common prompts to verify the content and presentation of templates.

This includes speeding up development work by generating boilerplate code, asking the AI models to review the quality of the code, and provide miscellaneous assistance during application development.  The licenses have, as of mid-2025, been deployed to a limited number of developers and specialists so that the impact of GitHub Copilot can be measured against its costs.

results: Provide help to developers in the form of IDE-based assistance for code generation, code review or code modification.  Once the pilot phase is over, an assessment of its usefulness will be made to see if the number of licenses is to be reduced, maintained or increased.

capabilities: Natural‑language Q&A; guided workflows; knowledge search; ticket triage; escalation to human agent; usage analytics.
